data.content:
## Migration Analysis

Your code is a **timeout enforcement** pattern with a **ThreadAbortException control flow** catch. Three APIs must go:

| Removed API | Why | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+ | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | No longer exists | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown in modern .NET | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        // CancellationTokenSource is IDisposable ŌĆö always wrap in using
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        Task<T> task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException when the
            // token fires, even if Task.Run's work doesn't check the token.
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            // Unwrap single-exception aggregates to match original behavior
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls

**1. The work doesn't magically stop.** `Thread.Abort` forcibly killed the thread; cooperative cancellation does not. `Task.WaitAsync` lets the *caller* stop waiting, but the delegate keeps running in the background until it finishes. If you need actual cancellation, pass the token into the work:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    Task<T> task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

    try
    {
        return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

Then callers check the token:
```csharp
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

**2. Don't forget to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`.** Leaking it causes timer and callback leaks. Always use `using`.

**3. `Task.WaitAsync` requires .NET 6+.** It's available on your .NET 8 target. Without it you'd need `Task.WhenAny(task, Task.Delay(timeout))`, which is more verbose.

**4. Blocking sync-over-async (`GetAwaiter().GetResult()`) is used here** to preserve the synchronous `T` return signature. If callers can be updated, prefer making this fully `async Task<T>`:

```csharp
public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
    Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    try
    {
        return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

**5. Truly uncooperative code** (third-party libs, native calls that can't accept a token) cannot be cancelled cooperatively. Move such work to a child **process** and use `Process.Kill()` ŌĆö this is the only safe equivalent of the old `Thread.Abort` force-kill semantics.
